tweet: #SEE $SEE  - Fleet not taken into account - A bidding war to get the best DMS supplier (Mobileye bought for c. $15bn at >50x net profit as an example). - The many applications of eye tracking of Seeing's quality; dimming a phone's brightness when the user looks tired, for example

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  I cannot express enough, though, how much further upside there can be to this (even though I wouldn't be too displeased with 50p a share!) Reasons:

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  An overall conservative fair value per share for Seeing Machines then (based on just automotive and aviation) once the cars hit the road could be judged as:  1.25 x (18 x 0.25 + 48 x 0.75) = 50.6p (roughly 400% upside from the current price). A mcap roughly ¬£1.9bn.

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  It is difficult to value aviation though given the relative opaqueness of the business - I'll again be cautious here and assign it 25% of the value I do to auto with significant upside skew.

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  Here is the kicker: auto is only one part of the business.  Seeing Machines believe that aviation (use in flight simulators and airplane pilot monitoring systems) could be as large a contributor as automotive to the business.

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  Seeing has negligible debt and assuming 0 cash at the time of valuation (as it will probably be negligible), we arrive at a price range for Seeing AUTOMOTIVE of 18p-48p (with the latter far more likely).

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  BTW - the market share and EBITDA margin assumptions are conservative.

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  Assuming:  - 100m cars produced a year - 40% market share - 30% EBITDA margin  Seeing would earn $60-120m EBITDA = c. ¬£45m-90m a year.  At a 15x EV/EBITDA multiple Seeing auto EV = ¬£675m-¬£1.35bn.  At 20x, ¬£900m-¬£1.8bn.

name: Shrey Srivastava
tweet: #SEE $SEE  Their current c. ¬£400m market cap is peanuts compared to what they could (and arguably should) be worth. Seeing's pricing is around $5-10 per car.
